<h1 class="hero-h">Gym lease <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">negotiation.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">The single most expensive document a first-time gym owner signs. The lease decisions made in 30 days lock in 10 years of cost structure, and the items most operators don't negotiate are usually the items the landlord is most willing to give. Here are the seven highest-leverage negotiation points, the traps to avoid, and the language to push back on.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The honest frame</span>
<h2 class="h2">Landlords negotiate; first-timers usually don't</h2>
<p class="body">Commercial landlords negotiate leases professionally; first-time gym owners negotiate one in their lifetime. The asymmetry is brutal. The first lease term offered is almost never the best the landlord will agree to, and getting to the better terms requires either professional representation (broker + attorney) or unusual patience.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>Always engage:</strong> a commercial real estate attorney ($2K-$6K for a single-tenant retail lease) and a tenant-side broker (paid by landlord, costs you nothing). The cost of professional representation pays back through a single negotiated TI bump or personal-guarantee carve-out.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The seven big items</span>
<h2 class="h2">Where the real money lives</h2>

<h3 class="h3">1. TI (tenant improvement) allowance</h3>
<p class="body">The single most-impactful number in the lease. TI is landlord-funded buildout capital amortized into rent.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Typical:</strong> $20-$40/sq ft for second-gen retail in Tier-2/3 markets. $40-$80/sq ft in Tier-1 or for first-gen/ground-up.</li>
<li><strong>For a 4,000 sq ft boutique:</strong> Going from $25/sq ft to $45/sq ft = $80K of effectively-free capital.</li>
<li><strong>Negotiate by trading:</strong> longer lease term (10 years vs 5+5), stronger personal guarantee, better credit story.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">2. Rent abatement (free rent during buildout)</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Typical:</strong> 4-6 months of free base rent for second-gen; 6-9 months for ground-up/heavy buildout.</li>
<li><strong>You still pay:</strong> CAM, utilities, insurance, real estate tax pass-throughs.</li>
<li><strong>Push for:</strong> abatement that starts at lease execution, not at certificate of occupancy.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">3. Base rent + annual escalators</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Typical:</strong> Year 1 base + 2-3% annual escalator. Push back on any landlord asking for 4%+ or CPI-uncapped.</li>
<li><strong>Cap CPI-based escalators</strong> at 3% if CPI-pegged is unavoidable.</li>
<li><strong>Watch for:</strong> "fair market value" reset clauses at year 5 or 7, these can balloon rent at a horrible moment.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">4. CAM and operating expense caps</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>What CAM is:</strong> Common Area Maintenance, your pro-rata share of landlord's costs for the building/center.</li>
<li><strong>Cap the annual increase:</strong> 5-7% year-over-year max, or push for a fixed CAM that doesn't increase.</li>
<li><strong>Exclude:</strong> capital expenditures, landlord's leasing commissions, costs related to other tenants' improvements.</li>
<li><strong>Audit rights:</strong> insist on the right to audit CAM charges annually. Landlords occasionally err in their own favor.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">5. Personal guarantee scope</h3>
<p class="body">Almost always required from first-time operators. But scope is negotiable.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Push for limited recourse:</strong> Capped at 12-18 months of base rent.</li>
<li><strong>Burn-off clause:</strong> Guarantee reduces or eliminates after years 2 or 3 if rent is paid on time.</li>
<li><strong>"Good guy" guarantee:</strong> Limits your liability if you give written notice and vacate by a specified date. Common and reasonable.</li>
<li><strong>Joint and several with spouse:</strong> Decline. Sign as the LLC owner only, not as your spouse too.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">6. Use clause + assignment + sublease</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Use clause:</strong> Make it broad. "Fitness center and related uses" beats "CrossFit affiliate", gives you flexibility if you pivot the format.</li>
<li><strong>Assignment rights:</strong> Right to assign the lease to a buyer if you sell the business. Critical to exit value.</li>
<li><strong>Sublease rights:</strong> Right to sublease unused space (e.g., a personal training studio inside a larger box).</li>
<li><strong>Landlord consent:</strong> "Not to be unreasonably withheld", push for this language on all consents.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">7. Exit clauses</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Kickout rights:</strong> Right to terminate at year 3 or 5 if revenue thresholds aren't met. Hard to get in strong markets, possible in weak ones.</li>
<li><strong>Co-tenancy clauses:</strong> Right to reduced rent or termination if anchor tenants leave the center (huge in retail centers where Whole Foods or grocery anchor matters).</li>
<li><strong>Casualty / condemnation:</strong> Clear language on termination rights if the property is damaged.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The math</span>
<h2 class="h2">What good negotiation actually saves</h2>
<p class="body">Worked example: 4,000 sq ft boutique studio, 10-year lease at $35/sq ft NNN base rent.</p>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>First offer</th><th>Well-negotiated</th><th>10-year impact</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>TI allowance</td><td>$25/sq ft = $100K</td><td>$45/sq ft = $180K</td><td>+$80K (essentially free capital)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Rent abatement</td><td>3 months</td><td>5 months</td><td>+$23K (avoided rent)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Annual escalator</td><td>3.5%</td><td>2.5%</td><td>~$25K (over 10 yrs)</td></tr>
<tr><td>CAM cap</td><td>None</td><td>5%/year cap</td><td>~$15-$40K (depends on landlord behavior)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Personal guarantee</td><td>Unlimited, full term</td><td>18-month rolling, burns off year 4</td><td>Materially lower personal risk</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Total cash + risk impact</strong></td><td></td><td></td><td><strong>~$140-$170K over lease term</strong></td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>The pro-rep ROI:</strong> A $4K-$6K attorney + tenant broker pair usually negotiates 5-10x their cost in lease improvements. Skipping this is the single most-expensive false economy in opening a gym.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Traps</span>
<h2 class="h2">Five lease traps to push back on</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>1. Relocation clauses.</strong> "Landlord may relocate tenant to comparable space", never sign this. Your members built drive-time habits around your address.</li>
<li><strong>2. Exclusive use clauses (yours and theirs).</strong> Demand exclusivity in your use category (no other fitness tenant in the center). Push back on the landlord's exclusivity restrictions that limit your offerings.</li>
<li><strong>3. Percentage rent.</strong> Common in retail center leases, extra rent if revenue exceeds a threshold. Decline or set the threshold very high.</li>
<li><strong>4. Estoppel + SNDA on landlord-favorable terms.</strong> Required by lenders; sign with attorney review.</li>
<li><strong>5. Annual statement audit limitations.</strong> Some leases limit your right to audit CAM. Reject, you need the right to verify charges.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

